  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "\"Cogalent pruning\" doesn't appear to be a standard or recognized term that I'm familiar with — whether in horticulture, machine learning, mathematics, or other fields where \"pruning\" is commonly used.\n\nA few possibilities:\n\n1. **Possible misspelling or alternate term** — Could you have meant:\n   - **Coherent pruning** (sometimes used in neural networks)?\n   - **Covalent** (a chemistry term, though \"covalent pruning\" isn't standard either)?\n   - **Cogent pruning** (perhaps a specific technique from a paper)?\n\n2. **Domain-specific jargon** — If this is from a particular paper, textbook, or specialized field, could you share the context? That would help me figure out what's being referred to.\n\n3. **Very new or niche term** — If it's from recent research I may not have information on it.\n\nCould you provide more context about where you encountered this term? I'd rather admit I don't know than make something up.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "\"Cogalent pruning\" doesn't appear to be a standard or recognized term that I'm familiar with — in machine learning, horticulture, graph theory, or any other field I can identify.\n\nA few possibilities:\n\n1. **Possible typo or misspelling** — Could you be thinking of:\n   - **Coherent pruning** (in neural networks)?\n   - **Cogent pruning**?\n   - Something else?\n\n2. **Very niche or new term** — It may be a specialized term from a specific paper, framework, or domain that I don't have information about.\n\n3. **Made-up or fictional term** — It's also possible the term doesn't actually exist.\n\nCould you provide more context about where you encountered \"cogalent pruning\"? For example, was it in a research paper, a gardening guide, a software documentation, or somewhere else? With more context, I can give you a much better answer — or confirm if it's a term I genuinely don't know rather than guessing.",
